http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Thu 18 Oct 2012
Source: examiner.com [edited]
http://www.examiner.com/article/halifax-s-spike-syphilis-cases-linked-to-online-connections


Health officials in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada, say they have seen a spike in cases of the sexually transmitted infection syphilis this year and point to sexual liaisons met on the Internet as a significant factor, according to a CBC News report 18 Oct 2012.

Capital District Health Authority senior epidemiologist, Holly D'Angelo-Scott says 47 men have tested positive for the sexually transmitted infection so far this year, as compared to 35 cases in all of 2011. Many of the syphilis cases reported are men who met their sexual partner on the Internet, D'Angelo-Scott tells CBC News. "That's probably a common link between some of the cases."

Since 2009, all the 100-plus cases reported in the city have been reported in men, and health officials say it may spread beyond men who have sex with men (MSM) to women.

Halifax is not the only place that is establishing a link between an increase in syphilis and anonymous sexual partners met online. Just last month in Christchurch, New Zealand, health officials said anonymous sexual hookups arranged over the Internet is the likely reason for an "incredible rise" in syphilis young gay and bisexual men in the city.

Last year in Alberta, where health officials were trying to battle their own syphilis problems, they even came up with a parody website, plentyofsyph.com, in an attempt to combat their syphilis problem [ProMED-mail post Syphilis - USA, Canada 20081112.3561]. The website has since been taken down and replaced.

For more information on syphilis, check out the CDC website [http://www.cdc.gov/std/syphilis/stdfact-syphilis.htm].

[Byline: Robert Herriman]

