[In the USA, as the rate of primary and secondary (infectious) syphilis decreased among homosexual and bisexual males, largely because of changes in sexual behavior due to AIDS, a spike in the rate of infectious syphilis occurred in the late 1980s among heterosexual men, women, and neonates (congenital syphilis) that was attributed to epidemic of crack cocaine use and exchange of sex for drugs. Cases of syphilis again dropped from 1990 to 2000. In 2000, the rate of primary and secondary syphilis in the United States was 2.1 cases per 100 000 population, the lowest since reporting began in 1941. From 2001 to 2004, the primary and secondary syphilis rate increased nationally to 2.7, primarily as a result of increases in cases among men who have sex with men (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5510a1.htm).

As in the USA, the rates of infectious syphilis in Canada have been increasing since about 2000. In Canada, the male-to-female rate ratio increased from 1.5:1.0 in 1999 to 6.4:1.0 in 2008, reflecting that more males than females were reported with infectious syphilis, and this disparity increased over time (http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/std-mts/report/sti-its2008/05-eng.php): In 2008, men accounted for 86.1 percent of reported cases. Between 1999 and 2008, the rate in men increased from 0.7 to 7.3 per 100 000 and in women increased from 0.5 to 1.1 per 100 000. In men, the highest reported rate of infectious syphilis was shared between 25-29 year olds and 30-39 year olds (13.3 per 100 000) (http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/std-mts/report/sti-its2008/05-eng.php). Together, these age groups accounted for almost 40 percent of reported cases in men in 2008. In women, the highest reported rate was in 20-24 year olds (3.6 per 100 000). In males, the greatest increase in reported rates of infectious syphilis between 1999 and 2008 was in 25-29 year olds.

In New Brunswick, the Canadian province that borders Nova Scotia, ProMED-mail recently reported [Syphilis - Canada: (NB) 20120210.1038543] an infectious syphilis outbreak that is characterized as involving mainly males, most of whom are men who have sex with men (MSM). Many reported having multiple sex partners, including casual and/or anonymous partners, and at least 5 of the cases were co-infected with HIV. Reported increases in incidence of infectious syphilis among MSM have been characterized by high rates of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) co-infection, high-risk sexual behavior, use of drugs such as methamphetamines, and use of Internet chat rooms to meet sex partners (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5510a1.htm).

Reported increases in the incidence of infectious syphilis among MSM have been attributed in part to "HIV prevention fatigue," which appears to limit effective condom use and to result in high-risk sexual behavior associated with use of drugs or the use of the Internet, which can also lead to unsafe sex with multiple partners.

Nova Scotia in Eastern Canada is one of Canada's 3 Maritime Provinces (New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, and Prince Edward Island). Nova Scotia is bounded in the west by New Brunswick. See http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/84/Nova_Scotia%2C_Canada.svg to locate Nova Scotia on a map of Canada.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Canada can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1ALd. - Mod.ML]
